<p class="EnTeteTranscription">Jones, John. Letter to Judge Adam Mabane, 1787, with a copy of Jones's testimony 1783. An electronic transcription. MFTP #0003</p><div class="ContenuPage">
<p style="text-align:justify;">You are adroit in the Art of developing; m<span class="AddHand-editors">[y]</span> <span class="AddHand-editors">[inter]</span>rogatories would afford you an opportunity of de<span class="AddHand-editors">[veloping]</span> the interior Cabinet: Heavens, what a perspective!</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">I coincide with you that this action was attended by <span style="text-decoration:underline;">facts of a very serious &amp; important Nature</span>; May I ask you if that is not the strongest inducement for a Judge to be Cautious, deliberate and dispassionate in pronouncing Judgement, to lay a side prejudice and to avoid a hasty &amp; precipitate Decision?  Can there be a better reason for Calm and cool reflection?</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">You have declined enumerating facts; be not angry that I do.</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">For a Judge to be challenged on the <span class="AddHand-author">B</span>ench, as unfit &amp; incompetent to sit there, because he had advised in private to prosecute the action, <span style="text-decoration:underline;">is a fact of a very serious &amp; important Nature</span>.</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">For a Judge to shew to a spectator in the Court a Judgement in the Action against M<sup>r</sup> Cochrane which he had brought ready made into Court, and to say <span class="AddHand-author">(in answer to expostulations which the said spectator was allowed to make) </span>that it would not militate against the interests of his Constituents <span style="text-decoration:underline;">is a fact of a very serious &amp; important Nature</span>.</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">For a Judge to declare on the Bench that he was ready <span class="AddHand-author">(as a member of the Legisaltive Council) </span>to assist in amending Old Laws &amp; making new Ones for the good of the King's Subjects, and <span class="DelHand-author">never</span><span class="AddHand-author"> not</span> <span class="AddHand-author">to </span>do it, is <span style="text-decoration:underline;">a fact of a very serious and important nature</span>.</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;"><span class="DelHand-author">For a Judge who is a Member of the Legislative Council to be <span class="Gap">[&#8230;]</span> &amp; intriguing in that Council to counter act the gracious intentions of his Sovereign</span></p>
<p style="text-align:right;">is</p>

